<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Odisha</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">The <em>Soul of Ancient Kalinga</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Odisha — the ancient land of Kalinga — is one of the Indian subcontinent's most spiritually resonant, artistically rich and ecologically extraordinary states. The Battle of Kalinga in 261 BC, fought on Odisha's soil, changed the course of world history: Emperor Ashoka witnessed the carnage of 100,000 dead, renounced war and embraced Buddhism — his subsequent moral edicts spread across Asia and influenced the foundations of modern international law. The land that could transform a conqueror into a pacifist carries within it something of extraordinary civilizational power. The Jagannath Temple at Puri — where Lord Jagannath (a form of Vishnu with pre-Hindu tribal roots) has been worshipped for over 1,000 years — is one of Hinduism's four Dhams (cardinal pilgrimage sites). The Rath Yatra — the annual chariot procession of Jagannath — is the world's oldest, largest and most powerful religious chariot festival, drawing millions who pull the giant wooden chariots through Puri's Grand Road. The word "juggernaut" in the English language derives from "Jagannath" — the unstoppable force of the chariot. The Konark Sun Temple — a UNESCO World Heritage Site — is a 13th-century architectural marvel built in the form of the sun god's colossal chariot with 24 intricately carved wheels and seven horses. The quality of its erotic sculpture rivals Khajuraho; its astronomical precision rivals Jantar Mantar. The Lingaraj Temple of Bhubaneswar and the city's 500+ ancient temples make it the "Temple City of India." Odisha's tribal population — 22% of the state, over 60 distinct tribes including Kondh, Santali, Gond, Saura, Juang and Dongria Kondh — represent some of the most culturally intact indigenous communities in South Asia. The Eastern Ghats of Odisha shelter these communities in forests of extraordinary biodiversity. The state's coastline — 485 km of the Bay of Bengal — is the nesting ground for the olive ridley sea turtle, which arrives in its millions at Gahirmatha and Rushikulya beaches for the world's largest mass nesting (arribada) event. Odisha's arts — Pattachitra painting, Odissi dance (one of India's eight classical forms), Gotipua, Chhau dance, silver filigree, stone carving and palm leaf manuscripts — represent a civilization that has never stopped creating. This is India at its most ancient, most creative and most quietly magnificent.</p>
