const placesData=[
{emoji:"🛕",name:"Jagannath Temple, Puri",location:"Puri",desc:"One of Hinduism's four sacred Dhams — the Jagannath Temple has stood for over 1,000 years and is among the most spiritually powerful places on earth. Lord Jagannath — with his distinctive wide eyes and unfinished arms — is a pre-Hindu tribal deity absorbed into the Vaishnava tradition, making this temple uniquely inclusive. The daily prasad (Mahaprasad) fed to 10,000+ people is cooked in the world's largest temple kitchen. Non-Hindus are not permitted inside — but the surrounding Dham vibrates with devotion.",fee:["Free (Hindus only)"]},
{emoji:"☀️",name:"Konark Sun Temple",location:"Puri District",desc:"UNESCO World Heritage Site — a 13th-century architectural masterpiece conceived as the colossal stone chariot of the sun god Surya. Twenty-four intricately carved wheels (functioning as sundials), seven stone horses and hundreds of erotic sculpture panels cover every surface. Built by King Narasimhadeva I of the Eastern Ganga dynasty in 1250 AD. The precision of its astronomical alignments — equinox sunrises through the entrance gate — reveals a civilization of extraordinary scientific knowledge.",fee:["Rs.40 Indians","Rs.600 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🦭",name:"Chilika Lake",location:"Puri-Khordha-Ganjam",desc:"Asia's largest brackish water lagoon — 1,100 sq km of shimmering water teeming with Irrawaddy dolphins (found only here and in the Ganges), flamingos, over 160 migratory bird species and extraordinary fish diversity. A Ramsar Convention wetland of international importance. The Nalaban Island bird sanctuary within the lake turns pink with flamingos from November to February. Boat rides to the dolphin point at dawn are among Odisha's most memorable experiences.",fee:["Boat charges apply"]},
{emoji:"🐊",name:"Bhitarkanika National Park",location:"Kendrapara District",desc:"One of the largest mangrove ecosystems in Asia and the home of India's largest population of saltwater crocodiles — the most dangerous reptile on earth, reaching 6 meters in length. The Bhitarkanika mangrove labyrinth shelters kingfishers, sea eagles, monitor lizards, spotted deer and the rare Irrawaddy dolphin. The Gahirmatha beach at its edge hosts the world's largest olive ridley sea turtle nesting event — millions of turtles arrive together.",fee:["Paid"]},
{emoji:"🏛️",name:"Bhubaneswar Temple City",location:"Bhubaneswar, Khordha",desc:"Once home to over 7,000 temples, Bhubaneswar still has 500+ functioning ancient temples in various states of extraordinary preservation. The Lingaraj Temple (11th century) is the largest and most magnificent; the Mukteshwar Temple (10th century) is the most exquisitely proportioned; the Rajarani Temple (11th century) has the finest sculpture. Together they form the most complete surviving record of the Kalinga school of temple architecture.",fee:["Free (Hindus only at Lingaraj)"]},
{emoji:"🏺",name:"Udayagiri-Khandagiri Caves",location:"Bhubaneswar",desc:"2nd–1st century BC rock-cut caves carved for Jain monks by the Kalinga king Kharavela — one of ancient India's most powerful rulers. The Rani Gumpha (Queen's Cave) has elaborately carved friezes depicting royal processions, women, animals and Kharavela's military victories. The Hathigumpha (Elephant Cave) inscription is one of the most important historical records of ancient India.",fee:["Rs.15 Indians","Rs.200 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🐢",name:"Gahirmatha & Olive Ridley Turtles",location:"Jagatsinghpur District",desc:"The world's largest mass nesting site of olive ridley sea turtles — every winter, 300,000 to 800,000 turtles arrive simultaneously on Gahirmatha beach in the mass nesting event called arribada. The spectacle of hundreds of thousands of turtles covering every inch of beach, digging nests and laying eggs is one of nature's most extraordinary events. The Indian Navy and forest department protect the beach during nesting season.",fee:["Protected — permit required"]},
{emoji:"🦅",name:"Simlipal Tiger Reserve",location:"Mayurbhanj District",desc:"One of India's largest tiger reserves — 2,750 sq km of dense sal forest in the Eastern Ghats of north Odisha. Home to tigers, elephants, leopards, gaur, wild dogs, 231 species of orchid and extraordinary butterfly diversity. The tribal communities (Ho, Santali, Kharia) living in and around the reserve have profound ecological knowledge. The Barehipani Falls (399 meters) and Joranda Falls within the reserve are among Odisha's finest.",fee:["Paid"]},
{emoji:"⚔️",name:"Dhauli Shanti Stupa — Ashokan Rock Edicts",location:"Bhubaneswar (Dhauli Hills)",desc:"The site of the Battle of Kalinga (261 BC) — the battle that transformed Emperor Ashoka from a conqueror into a Buddhist pacifist whose moral edicts shaped world history. The hilltop Shanti Stupa (built jointly by India and Japan) overlooks the Daya river valley where the battle was fought. The original Ashokan rock edicts are carved into a natural rock face at the base — some of the most historically significant inscriptions on earth.",fee:["Free"]},
{emoji:"🌊",name:"Puri Beach & Chandrabhaga",location:"Puri District",desc:"Puri's beach — where the Bay of Bengal meets the sacred town — is one of India's most spiritually charged coastlines. Pilgrims bathe at the Swargadwara ghat while fishermen launch their traditional fishing boats beyond the surf. Chandrabhaga beach near Konark is where the Chandrabhaga Mela is held — one of Odisha's most beautiful small festivals. The entire 485-km coastline of Odisha is lined with similar stories.",fee:["Free"]}
