const artsData=[
{emoji:"🖼️",name:"Pattachitra Painting",location:"Raghurajpur Village, Puri District",desc:"One of India's oldest surviving scroll painting traditions — intricate narrative paintings on cloth (patta) or palm leaf depicting stories of Lord Jagannath, the Ramayana and Mahabharata. Natural colors from stone, leaves and flowers. The village of Raghurajpur near Puri is entirely composed of Pattachitra artists — every home is a studio. GI-tagged, internationally collected and recently exhibited at the Victoria and Albert Museum."},
{emoji:"💃",name:"Odissi Classical Dance",location:"Statewide",desc:"One of India's eight classical dance forms — considered the oldest surviving classical dance tradition in India, with roots in the devadasi (temple dancer) tradition and documented in 2nd-century BC temple sculptures at Udayagiri. Characterized by the tribhanga (triple bend) body posture, fluid movement and expressive abhinaya (mime). Guru Kelucharan Mohapatra revived Odissi from near-extinction in the 1950s. Now performed worldwide."},
{emoji:"🥁",name:"Gotipua & Chhau Dance",location:"Puri, Mayurbhanj, Baripada",desc:"Gotipua — young boys dressed as women performing acrobatic devotional dance dedicated to Lord Krishna — is one of Odisha's most distinctive performing traditions, considered the precursor of Odissi. Mayurbhanj Chhau — a vigorous martial dance using elaborate animal and mythological masks — is UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage. The Baripada Chhau festival is one of India's most extraordinary folk performance events."},
{emoji:"🔩",name:"Silver Filigree (Tarakasi)",location:"Cuttack",desc:"Cuttack's silver filigree craft — Tarakasi — is one of India's most refined metal crafts. Thin silver wires are twisted, bent and soldered without solder into intricate lacework patterns of flowers, peacocks and geometric designs. The Cuttack craftsmen produce jewelry, decorative items and the spectacular silver ornaments worn by the Jagannath idols during festivals. GI-tagged, internationally exhibited. Each piece takes days to make."},
{emoji:"🪡",name:"Sambalpuri Saree & Ikat Weaving",location:"Sambalpur, Bargarh, Sonepur",desc:"The Sambalpuri saree — woven in the Mahanadi river towns of western Odisha — uses a tie-and-dye (ikat) technique where threads are resist-dyed before weaving to create geometric patterns of extraordinary precision. The Sambalpuri weave requires the weaver to visualize the final pattern in reverse from the thread stage. GI-tagged. The Bomkai, Pasapalli and Sonepuri sarees from this region are among India's most prized textiles."},
{emoji:"📜",name:"Palm Leaf Manuscript — Talapatrachitra",location:"Puri, Kendrapara",desc:"An ancient tradition of illustrated manuscripts inscribed on palm leaves — the talipot palm leaves are dried, treated and inscribed with a sharp stylus. The incisions are rubbed with lampblack to reveal the text and illustrations. Libraries of these manuscripts preserve ancient Sanskrit and Odia texts, medicinal knowledge and ritual calendars. Some survive from the 12th century. Living practitioners still create new manuscripts alongside Pattachitra."}
