const traditionsData=[
{emoji:"🎡",name:"Rath Yatra — Jagannath's Chariot Festival",location:"Puri — June/July",desc:"The world's oldest, largest and most powerful chariot festival — held annually on Ashadha Shuddha Dwitiya. The three colossal wooden chariots of Jagannath (45 feet), Balabhadra and Subhadra are pulled by hundreds of thousands of devotees through the 3-km Grand Road to the Gundicha Temple. The chariots are rebuilt fresh every year from specific wood. The English word 'juggernaut' derives from 'Jagannath' — a measure of the festival's legendary power."},
{emoji:"🌊",name:"Chandrabhaga Mela — Magha Saptami",location:"Chandrabhaga Beach, Konark — February",desc:"One of Odisha's most beautiful small festivals — on Magha Saptami (seventh day of the bright fortnight of Magha), devotees bathe at the Chandrabhaga river mouth at sunrise, worshipping the sun just as the Konark temple was built to honor. Thousands gather on the beach. The combination of Konark's silhouette against the winter sunrise and the sound of the sea at devotional time is extraordinary."},
{emoji:"🎭",name:"Dhanuyatra — World's Largest Open Theatre",location:"Bargarh — December/January",desc:"Recognized by the Guinness Book as the world's largest open-air theatre — an 11-day festival in Bargarh town transforming the entire town into a stage. The story of Krishna killing his uncle Kansa is performed by 50,000 actors across a 10-km stage that is the entire town. Every resident becomes a character. No tickets, no audience/actor separation. The most genuinely participatory theatrical event in the world."},
{emoji:"🌸",name:"Puri Beach Festival & Konark Dance Festival",location:"Puri and Konark — December",desc:"The Konark Dance Festival — held every year in December against the backdrop of the illuminated Sun Temple — is one of India's most spectacular classical dance events. Bharatanatyam, Odissi, Manipuri, Kathak and Kuchipudi performers dance on an open-air stage with the UNESCO World Heritage temple as backdrop. The Puri Beach Festival runs simultaneously with sand art, traditional crafts and cultural performances."},
{emoji:"🎉",name:"Raja Parba — Women's Festival",location:"Statewide — June",desc:"Odisha's unique three-day festival celebrating the earth's menstruation (the onset of the monsoon season) — the earth goddess Bhudevi is considered to be menstruating and therefore resting. Swings are hung from every tree; young women dress in new clothes, eat special sweets and play on the swings. No farming is done for three days. Raja Parba is one of India's most original and ecologically rooted festivals."},
{emoji:"🪔",name:"Kumar Purnima",location:"Statewide — October",desc:"Odisha's uniquely beautiful festival for young women — on the full moon night of Ashwin, unmarried girls pray to Kartik (Kumar — the eternal youth) for a good husband. They decorate courtyards with alpona (floor art), light lamps in the shape of earthen boats (diyas) and float them on water. The night sky reflected in village ponds full of floating lamps is one of Odisha's most hauntingly beautiful seasonal images."}
