const cuisinesData=[
{emoji:"🍚",name:"Pakhala Bhata — Fermented Rice",location:"Statewide — Summer Classic",desc:"Odisha's most distinctive everyday food — cooked rice soaked overnight in water until slightly fermented, served cold the next day with fried vegetables, roasted potato, raw onion, green chili and lime. The fermentation creates a tangy, probiotic-rich dish that cools the body in Odisha's hot summers. Pakhala Dibasa (Pakhala Day) celebrated every March is a social media phenomenon — Odias worldwide share their pakhala plates with pride."},
{emoji:"🍡",name:"Dalma — Odisha's Signature Dal",location:"Statewide",desc:"Lentils cooked with raw vegetables (raw banana, pumpkin, raw papaya, drumstick) and tempered with panch phutana (five-spice: mustard, fenugreek, cumin, anise and dried chili) — the definitive Odia dal. No tomato, no onion, no garlic. The natural sweetness of the vegetables and the earthiness of the lentils create a dish of extraordinary nutritional depth. Dalma is also the prasad of the Jagannath Temple — offered to the deity daily."},
{emoji:"🐟",name:"Macha Besara — Mustard Fish Curry",location:"Coastal Odisha",desc:"Fish cooked in a sharp mustard-poppy seed paste with turmeric and green chili — the signature fish preparation of coastal Odisha. The Odia mustard paste is ground slightly coarser than Bengali shorshe, giving a more textured bite. Rohu, catla, hilsa and dozens of freshwater and sea fish from Odisha's rivers and coast find their way into this curry. The combination of mustard's sharpness and fish's sweetness is distinctly Odia."},
{emoji:"🍢",name:"Chhena Poda & Rasabali",location:"Puri, Nayagarh",desc:"Chhena Poda — 'burnt cheese' — is Odisha's most original contribution to Indian sweets. Fresh chhena (cottage cheese) mixed with sugar, cardamom and cashews, baked in a clay vessel until caramelized on all surfaces. It is the only Indian sweet that uses the Maillard reaction for flavor. Said to be Lord Jagannath's favorite sweet. Rasabali — deep-fried chhena discs soaked in thickened sweetened milk — is the Kendrapara district's pride."},
{emoji:"🌿",name:"Saga Bhaja & Forest Greens",location:"Tribal Odisha",desc:"Odisha's tribal communities bring extraordinary forest-food knowledge to the cuisine — dozens of wild greens (saga), mushrooms, tubers, flowers and fruits cooked simply with mustard oil, dried chili and panch phutana. Khatta saga (sorrel), kochila (bitter fruit), kendu leaf preparations and mahua flower dishes represent a forest-to-table cuisine of extraordinary variety. Red ant chutney (kai chutney) from Odisha's tribal belt is a delicacy prized for its protein and tangy-citrus flavor."},
{emoji:"🥘",name:"Santula — Vegetable Medley",location:"Statewide",desc:"Odisha's signature everyday vegetable preparation — a semi-dry medley of seasonal vegetables (potato, brinjal, raw banana, beans) cooked without oil in a small amount of water with turmeric and panch phutana, finished with a drizzle of mustard oil. The minimal intervention allows each vegetable's natural flavor to emerge. Santula is the dish that appears at every Odia meal, every day, in every household — the most democratic and nutritious expression of the cuisine."},
{emoji:"🍮",name:"Kheer Mohana & Temple Sweets",location:"Puri Jagannath Temple Tradition",desc:"The Puri Jagannath Temple's Mahaprasad is cooked in 752 earthen pots by 600 cooks in the world's largest temple kitchen. Fifty-six food items (Chhappan Bhog) are prepared daily using traditional wood-fired cooking. The kheer (rice pudding), laddoo, pitha and sweet rice preparations have been unchanged for centuries. Receiving the Mahaprasad is considered the ultimate blessing — believers say it cannot go stale regardless of how long it is kept."},
{emoji:"🫓",name:"Manda Pitha & Arisa Pitha",location:"Festival Foods — Statewide",desc:"Odisha has an extraordinary pitha (rice cake) culture with over 50 varieties made for different festivals. Manda Pitha — steamed rice dumplings stuffed with sweetened coconut and chhena — are made for Raja Parba and Durga Puja. Arisa Pitha — deep-fried rice flour discs sweetened with jaggery — are made for harvest festivals. Chakuli Pitha (fermented rice crepes) and Poda Pitha (baked rice cake) round out a sweet tradition of singular regional character."},
{emoji:"☕",name:"Koraput Coffee & Forest Produce",location:"Koraput, South Odisha",desc:"The tribal highlands of Koraput and Kondhamal district grow some of India's finest specialty coffee and turmeric. Kondhamal turmeric — GI-tagged — has extraordinary curcumin content and a bright aroma, grown by Kondh tribal farmers at 900+ meters. Koraput coffee, shade-grown by tribal communities in the Eastern Ghats, is now being recognised by specialty coffee buyers. These forest-agricultural products embody Odisha's tribal communities' sustainable relationship with their landscape."}
